he Young Lives study of 12,000 children growing up in Ethiopia, India, Peru and Vietnam over the past 15 years, this book draws on evidence on two cohorts of children, from 1 to 15 and from 8 to 22. It examines how poverty affects children's development in low and middle income countries, and how policy has been used to improve their lives, then goes on to show when key developmental differences occur. It uses new evidence to develop a framework of what matters most and when and outlines effective policy approaches to inform the no-one left behind Sustainable Development Goal agenda.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aChild developmentxLongitudinal studies. 0aPoor childrenvLongitudinal studies. 0aPovertyxSocial aspectsvLongitudinal studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Poverty & Homelessness.2bisacsh1 aDawes, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDornan, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311119668840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447348368zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447348368/original  a978-3-11-119668-8 Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA